09.11.2001
I worked in World Trade Center [WTC4] (New York Board of Trade; Commodities) and was there the morning of September 11th, I remember that day with extreme detail... I remember feeling the building shaking and the windows waving, I remember walking down the emergency stairwell, I remember exiting the building and dodging lifeless bodies bouncing off the floor, I remember making eye contact with a dead person, and I remember seeing the North Tower [WTC1] burning with a large hole going through it. I also remember looking up and seeing the second plane fly into the South Tower [WTC2], people jumping out of windows knowing their fate. I remember running down the street a while later because the building started to collapse, and I remember being covered in that dust thinking itâ€™s particles from humans. I also remember not having phone service and finally getting home after walking 20 miles from Manhattan to Queens to see my worried family and friends â€” I remember the look in my momâ€™s eyes when she saw I was still alive.

I remember with great detail, every feeling and emotion from that day. I remember smells, images, the energy, conversations with strangers and the blisters on my feet from walking in new dress shoes.

I also remember my friends and acquaintances that werenâ€™t lucky enough to make it out alive â€” and some never found. I remember the funerals I went to and I remember the families it effected... and still effects.

It wasnâ€™t until 3 years ago (2017) that I revisited Ground Zero, I had vivid flashbacks like a War Veteran having PTSD. I completely broke down and fell apart sobbing in my girlfriendâ€™s (now wifeâ€™s) arms. I didnâ€™t realize how much I buried and avoided those emotions until that moment.

Life is short and extremely unpredictable. Tell the people you care about you love them. Live life to the fullest. Forgive people and yourself. Stand up for people that canâ€™t/wonâ€™t stand up for themselves. Donâ€™t let your heart be filled with hatred. Take chances. Apologize. Itâ€™s ok to cry. Show compassion and empathy. Be kind to yourself and most importantly to me, take the â€œLONG JOURNEY HOMEâ€!
